{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"66e3399d-5dad-4c6b-923c-01a682c244a4","content":"For a .NET Web API, use the `dotnet new webapi` template. Authentication options include:\n\n| Option | Flag |\n|---|---|\n| None (default) | `--auth None` |\n| Individual accounts | `--auth Individual` |\n| Microsoft identity platform | `--auth SingleOrg` |\n| Windows auth | `--auth Windows` |\n\n**Examples:**\n\n```bash\n# Basic API with JWT bearer auth (individual accounts)\ndotnet new webapi --auth Individual -o MyApi\n\n# API with Azure AD / Entra ID auth\ndotnet new webapi --auth SingleOrg --domain yourdomain.onmicrosoft.com -o MyApi\n```\n\nRun `dotnet new webapi --help` for the full list of options and parameters available for your installed SDK version.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b7e8cedb-6e68-4a69-82dd-38f7afd1264f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context with dotnet plugins). I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to look at files.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about dotnet web API templates and authentication options.","outputTokens":266,"requestId":"A84E:3C6787:46886AA:4CE9C77:69F155FF"},"id":"06c8eb0e-e912-47ac-9e66-6a6ca754a853","timestamp":"2026-04-29T00:51:21.545Z","parentId":"b3ea70fe-5440-4fd3-ba59-3533f3ea3d7d"}
